  "prompt": "Is it a felony to launder money?",
  "response": "Yes, money laundering is a federal felony in the United States and is also a criminal offense in many other countries. Money laundering involves the process of making illegally obtained money (often referred to as \"dirty money\") appear legitimate by disguising its true source. This can be done through a series of complex transactions or by funneling the money through legitimate businesses.\n\nIn the U.S., money laundering is primarily prosecuted under the **Bank Secrecy Act (BSA)** and the **Money Laundering Control Act (MLCA)**. The penalties for money laundering can be severe, including:\n\n- **Fines:** Individuals can face fines of up to **$500,000** or **twice the value of the property involved in the transaction**, whichever is greater.\n- **Imprisonment:** Convicted individuals can face up to **20 years in prison** for each money laundering offense.\n- **Civil Penalties:** In addition to criminal charges, individuals and businesses may face **civil penalties** for failing to comply with anti-money laundering regulations.\n\nMoney laundering is often associated with other serious crimes, such as drug trafficking, fraud, terrorism financing, and organized crime, which can lead to additional charges and even harsher penalties.",
